<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05155p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05155p">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05155p"> 155(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bless &amp; curse</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Once, when St. Moling was praying in his church, the Devil visited him in purple raiment and distinguished form. On being challenged by the saint, he declared himself to be the Christ, but on Moling&apos;s raising the Gospel to disprove his claim, the Evil One confessed that he was Satan. &ldquo;Wherefore hast thou come?&rdquo; asked Moling. &ldquo;For a blessing,&rdquo; the Devil replied. &ldquo;Thou shall not have it,&rdquo; said Moling, &ldquo;for thou deservest it not.&rdquo; &ldquo;Well, then,&rdquo; said the Devil, &ldquo;bestow the full of a curse on me.&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Early Irish Religious Poetry] 112</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
